I chose a reasonably big telecom company churn dataset from kaggle. I chose this specific dataset because of its content and also because i didnât want to work with a dataset too small but also something not too big because of processing times. The number of lines on this dataset (50k training set + 20 test set) seems to be around the same order of magnitude as pipedrive has customers (95k companies as seen on the website) so it makes sense. The content made sense too because this data is meant for analysing churn which is an important question to be studied in any company.

churn_tr <- read.csv("cell2celltrain.csv", header = TRUE)

There are some missing values but for the few features the percentages are very low with under 2% so they are not probably a major cause for concern when we remove these lines later in the analysis. Analysis on missing values could be concidered to see if missingness is systematic but here i will not do that.

Below is a general look at all the categorical variables. Here we come a across a problem with the variable âHandsetPriceâ. First of all it is not really a categorical variable but is in this form only because it has a category called âUnknownâ. Another problem is that this category is overwhelmingly the largest category (28982 entries) so it canât just be ignored. One option here is to categorize all the other prices into âKnownâ. We will be loosing a lot of information with simplifying this variable down to two categories. Essentially doing this we can only look at wether having knowledge of the price (not what it is) gives us information about churn. Another option would be to impute this âUnknownâ category based on the other variables meaning basically making an educated guess (prediction) about the HandsetPrice by predicting it using the other variables. This would require quite a bit of work to make it as exact as possible because we would be imputing a lot of values (over 50%) and that can have big impact on the rest of the analysis. I think imputing with general mean would be unwise here because the âUnknownâ category is just so big and has a lot of weight. So for simplicities sake i will substitute all prices with âKnownâ to retain atleast some information from the feature. ServiceArea is not visualised here because it doesnât fit well on the plot and it is also unidentifiable

churn_tr %>%
  select_if(~class(.) == 'character') %>%
  select(-ServiceArea) %>%
  mutate(HandsetPrice = case_when(
    HandsetPrice != "Unknown" ~ "Known",
    TRUE ~ as.character(HandsetPrice)
  )) %>% 
  pivot_longer(!Churn, names_to = c("feature"), values_to = c("value")) %>% 
   ggplot(aes(x = value, fill = Churn))+
  geom_bar(position = "fill") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))+
  facet_wrap(~feature, scales = "free")+
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(colour = "gray30", size = 2))+
